{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565260"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:24:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:24:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17327"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17327"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.07,0.6,0.12,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69905"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10017"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55361"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3844"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11066"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23464"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69905"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of vulval itch and discomfort. She reports noticing a small lump in the area three months ago which has gradually increased in size. She has tried over-the-counter antifungal creams without improvement. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include perindopril and paracetamol. She is a current smoker with a 40 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm raised, irregular, ulcerated lesion on the right labia majora. There is no bleeding or discharge. No inguinal lymphadenopathy is detected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely pathophysiological mechanism for this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autoimmune destruction of vulval tissue","Bacterial invasion of epithelial cells","HPV-mediated DNA damage","Oestrogen-dependent cell proliferation","Direct chemical irritation from toxins"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suspicious for vulval squamous cell carcinoma (SCC). The pathophysiology of vulval SCC typically follows two distinct pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHPV-mediated DNA damage\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common mechanism, particularly in younger patients. High-risk human papillomavirus (HPV) types 16 and 18 integrate into the host cell DNA and express oncoproteins E6 and E7. E6 degrades p53 (preventing apoptosis of damaged cells), while E7 inactivates retinoblastoma protein (promoting cell cycle progression). This leads to genomic instability and eventual malignant transformation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune destruction\u003C/strong\u003E is not a primary mechanism in vulval SCC, although autoimmune conditions like lichen sclerosus can create a chronic inflammatory environment that increases cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial invasion\u003C/strong\u003E of epithelial cells is not a mechanism for vulval cancer development, although chronic infection and inflammation may contribute to cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen-dependent cell proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of endometrial cancer pathophysiology. Vulval SCC is not typically hormone-dependent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect chemical irritation\u003C/strong\u003E alone does not cause vulval cancer, although chronic irritation and inflammation may contribute to cancer development through the HPV-independent pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe HPV-independent pathway, which is more common in older patients like this one, typically involves p53 mutations and is associated with chronic inflammatory conditions. However, given the high prevalence of HPV infection, the HPV-dependent pathway remains the most likely mechanism even in older patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vulval squamous cell carcinoma commonly develops through human papillomavirus-dependent and independent pathways.","Chronic inflammation from conditions like lichen sclerosus increases risk of vulval cancer through p53 mutation.","High-risk HPV types 16 and 18 cause vulval cancer through integration into host DNA and expression of oncoproteins."],"references":["Olawaiye AB, Cuello MA, Rogers LJ. Cancer of the vulva: 2021 update. International Journal of Gynecology \u0026 Obstetrics. 2021;155(S1):7\u201318."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55361"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17327"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55361"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T22:38:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T22:39:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10017"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69905"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":nul